# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: spectral-graph-theory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In graph theory and computer science, an **adjacency matrix** is a square matrix used to represent a finite graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The elements of the matrix indicate whether pairs of vertices are adjacent or not within the graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In the special case of a finite simple graph, the adjacency matrix is a (0,1)-matrix with zeros on its diagonal.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] If the graph is undirected (i.e. all of its edges are bidirectional), the adjacency matrix is symmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The relationship between a graph and the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of its adjacency matrix is studied in spectral graph theory.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a graph should be distinguished from its incidence matrix, a different matrix representation whose elements indicate whether vertex–edge pairs are incident or not, and its degree matrix, which contains information about the degree of each vertex.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] For a simple graph with vertex set *U* = {*u*1, ..., *u**n*}, the adjacency matrix is a square *n* × *n* matrix A such that its element Aij is 1 when there is an edge from vertex *u*i to vertex *u*j, and 0 when there is no edge.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The diagonal elements of the matrix are all 0, since edges from a vertex to itself (loops) are not allowed in simple graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] It is also sometimes useful in algebraic graph theory to replace the nonzero elements with algebraic variables.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The same concept can be extended to multigraphs and graphs with loops by storing the number of edges between each two vertices in the corresponding matrix element, and by allowing nonzero diagonal elements.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Loops may be counted either once (as a single edge) or twice (as two vertex-edge incidences), as long as a consistent convention is followed.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Undirected graphs often use the latter convention of counting loops twice, whereas directed graphs typically use the former convention.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] where B is an *r* × *s* matrix, and 0*r*,*r* and 0*s*,*s* represent the *r* × *r* and *s* × *s* zero matrices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In this case, the smaller matrix B uniquely represents the graph, and the remaining parts of A can be discarded as redundant.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] B is sometimes called the *biadjacency matrix*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The biadjacency matrix is the *r* × *s* 0–1 matrix B in which *b**i*,*j* = 1 if and only if (*u**i*, *v**j*) ∈ *E*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] If G is a bipartite multigraph or weighted graph, then the elements b*i,j* are taken to be the number of edges between the vertices or the weight of the edge (*u**i*, *v**j*), respectively.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] An (*a*, *b*, *c*)-adjacency matrix A of a simple graph has *A**i*,*j* = *a* if (*i*, *j*) is an edge, b if it is not, and c on the diagonal.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The Seidel adjacency matrix is a (−1, 1, 0)-adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] This matrix is used in studying strongly regular graphs and two-graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix has in position (*i*, *j*) the distance between vertices vi and vj.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The distance is the length of a shortest path connecting the vertices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Unless lengths of edges are explicitly provided, the length of a path is the number of edges in it.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix resembles a high power of the adjacency matrix, but instead of telling only whether or not two vertices are connected (i.e., the connection matrix, which contains Boolean values), it gives the exact distance between them.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The convention followed here (for undirected graphs) is that each edge adds 1 to the appropriate cell in the matrix, and each loop (an edge from a vertex to itself) adds 2 to the appropriate cell on the diagonal in the matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] This allows the degree of a vertex to be easily found by taking the sum of the values in either its respective row or column in the adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph can be asymmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The former definition is commonly used in graph theory and social network analysis (e.g., sociology, political science, economics, psychology).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The latter is more common in other applied sciences (e.g., dynamical systems, physics, network science) where A is sometimes used to describe linear dynamics on graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Using the first definition, the in-degrees of a vertex can be computed by summing the entries of the corresponding column and the out-degree of vertex by summing the entries of the corresponding row.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] When using the second definition, the in-degree of a vertex is given by the corresponding row sum and the out-degree is given by the corresponding column sum.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a complete graph contains all ones except along the diagonal where there are only zeros.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an empty graph is a zero matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an undirected simple graph is symmetric, and therefore has a complete set of real eigenvalues and an orthogonal eigenvector basis.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The set of eigenvalues of a graph is the **spectrum** of the graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The greatest eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ is bounded above by the maximum degree.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] This can be seen as result of the Perron–Frobenius theorem, but it can be proved easily.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Let v be one eigenvector associated to $\lambda _{1}$ and x the entry in which v has maximum absolute value.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Without loss of generality assume vx is positive since otherwise you simply take the eigenvector -v, also associated to $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] For d-regular graphs, d is the first eigenvalue of A for the vector *v* = (1, ..., 1) (it is easy to check that it is an eigenvalue and it is the maximum because of the above bound).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The multiplicity of this eigenvalue is the number of connected components of G, in particular $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}$ for connected graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] It can be shown that for each eigenvalue $\lambda _{i}$ , its opposite $-\lambda _{i}=\lambda _{n+1-i}$ is also an eigenvalue of A if G is a bipartite graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In particular −d is an eigenvalue of any d-regular bipartite graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The difference $\lambda _{1}-\lambda _{2}$ is called the spectral gap and it is related to the expansion of G.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] It is also useful to introduce the spectral radius of A denoted by $\lambda (G)=\max _{\left|\lambda _{i}\right|<d}|\lambda _{i}|$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] This bound is tight in the Ramanujan graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Suppose two directed or undirected graphs *G*1 and *G*2 with adjacency matrices *A*1 and *A*2 are given.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In particular, *A*1 and *A*2 are similar and therefore have the same minimal polynomial, characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, determinant and trace.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] These can therefore serve as isomorphism invariants of graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] However, two graphs may possess the same set of eigenvalues but not be isomorphic.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Such linear operators are said to be isospectral.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] If A is the adjacency matrix of the directed or undirected graph G, then the matrix *A**n* (i.e., the matrix product of n copies of A) has an interesting interpretation: the element (*i*, *j*) gives the number of (directed or undirected) walks of length n from vertex i to vertex j.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] If n is the smallest nonnegative integer, such that for some i, j, the element (*i*, *j*) of *A**n* is positive, then n is the distance between vertex i and vertex j.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] A great example of how this is useful is in counting the number of triangles in an undirected graph G, which is exactly the trace of *A*3 divided by 3 or 6 depending on whether the graph is directed or not.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] We divide by those values to compensate for the overcounting of each triangle.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In an undirected graph, each triangle will be counted twice for all three nodes, because the path can be followed clockwise or counterclockwise : ijk or ikj.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix can be used to determine whether or not the graph is connected.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] If a directed graph has a nilpotent adjacency matrix (i.e., if there exists n such that *A**n* is the zero matrix), then it is a directed acyclic graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix may be used as a data structure for the representation of graphs in computer programs for manipulating graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Boolean data types are used, such as `True` and `False` in Python.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The main alternative data structure, also in use for this application, is the adjacency list.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] The space needed to represent an adjacency matrix and the time needed to perform operations on them is dependent on the matrix representation chosen for the underlying matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Sparse matrix representations only store non-zero matrix entries and implicitly represent the zero entries.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] They can, for example, be used to represent sparse graphs without incurring the space overhead from storing the many zero entries in the adjacency matrix of the sparse graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] In the following section the adjacency matrix is assumed to be represented by an array data structure so that zero and non-zero entries are all directly represented in storage.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Although slightly more succinct representations are possible, this method gets close to the information-theoretic lower bound for the minimum number of bits needed to represent all n-vertex graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] For storing graphs in text files, fewer bits per byte can be used to ensure that all bytes are text characters, for instance by using a Base64 representation.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Besides avoiding wasted space, this compactness encourages locality of reference.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] However, for a large sparse graph, adjacency lists require less storage space, because they do not waste any space representing edges that are *not* present.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] An alternative form of adjacency matrix (which, however, requires a larger amount of space) replaces the numbers in each element of the matrix with pointers to edge objects (when edges are present) or null pointers (when there is no edge).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] It is also possible to store edge weights directly in the elements of an adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Besides the space tradeoff, the different data structures also facilitate different operations.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] Finding all vertices adjacent to a given vertex in an adjacency list is as simple as reading the list, and takes time proportional to the number of neighbors.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] With an adjacency matrix, an entire row must instead be scanned, which takes a larger amount of time, proportional to the number of vertices in the whole graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/adjacency-matrix] On the other hand, testing whether there is an edge between two given vertices can be determined at once with an adjacency matrix, while requiring time proportional to the minimum degree of the two vertices with the adjacency list.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The **algebraic connectivity** (also known as **Fiedler value** or **Fiedler eigenvalue** after Miroslav Fiedler) of a graph *G* is the second-smallest eigenvalue (counting multiple eigenvalues separately) of the Laplacian matrix of *G*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] This eigenvalue is greater than 0 if and only if *G* is a connected graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] This is a corollary to the fact that the number of times 0 appears as an eigenvalue in the Laplacian is the number of connected components in the graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The magnitude of this value reflects how well connected the overall graph is.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] It has been used in analyzing the robustness and synchronizability of networks.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The algebraic connectivity of undirected graphs with nonnegative weights is $a(G)\geq 0$ , with the inequality being strict if and only if G is connected.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] However, the algebraic connectivity can be negative for general directed graphs, even if *G* is a connected graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] Furthermore, the value of the algebraic connectivity is bounded above by the traditional (vertex) connectivity of a graph, ${\text{algebraic connectivity}}\leq {\text{connectivity}}$ , unless the graph is complete (the algebraic connectivity of a complete graph Kn is its order n).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] For an undirected connected graph with nonnegative edge weights, *n* vertices, and diameter *D*, the algebraic connectivity is also known to be bounded below by ${\textstyle {\frac {1}{nD}}}$ , and in fact (in a result due to Brendan McKay) by ${\textstyle {\frac {4}{nD}}}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] In random graphs, the algebraic connectivity decreases with the number of vertices, and increases with the average degree.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The exact definition of the algebraic connectivity depends on the type of Laplacian used.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] Fan Chung has developed an extensive theory using a rescaled version of the Laplacian, eliminating the dependence on the number of vertices, so that the bounds are somewhat different.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] In models of synchronization on networks, such as the Kuramoto model, the Laplacian matrix arises naturally, so the algebraic connectivity gives an indication of how easily the network will synchronize.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] Other measures, such as the average distance (characteristic path length) can also be used, and in fact the algebraic connectivity is closely related to the (reciprocal of the) average distance.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The algebraic connectivity also relates to other connectivity attributes, such as the isoperimetric number, which is bounded below by half the algebraic connectivity.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The original theory related to algebraic connectivity was produced by Miroslav Fiedler.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] In his honor the eigenvector associated with the algebraic connectivity has been named the **Fiedler vector**.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The Fiedler vector can be used to partition a graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The negative values are associated with the poorly connected vertex 6, and the neighbouring articulation point, vertex 4; while the positive values are associated with the other vertices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The signs of the values in the Fiedler vector can therefore be used to partition this graph into two components: ${\textstyle \{1,2,3,5\},\{4,6\}}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] Alternatively, the value of 0.069 (which is close to zero) can be placed in a class of its own, partitioning the graph into three components: ${\textstyle \{1,2,5\},\{3\},\{4,6\}}$ or moved to the other partition ${\textstyle \{1,2,5\},\{3,4,6\}}$ , as pictured.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/algebraic-connectivity] The squared values of the components of the Fiedler vector, summing up to one since the vector is normalized, can be interpreted as probabilities of the corresponding data points to be assigned to the sign-based partition.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] In theoretical computer science, graph theory, and mathematics, the **conductance** is a parameter of a Markov chain that is closely tied to its mixing time, that is, how rapidly the chain converges to its stationary distribution, should it exist.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Equivalently, the conductance can be viewed as a parameter of a directed graph, in which case it can be used to analyze how quickly random walks in the graph converge.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] The conductance of a graph is closely related to the Cheeger constant of the graph, which is also known as the edge expansion or the isoperimetic number.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] However, due to subtly different definitions, the conductance and the edge expansion do not generally coincide if the graphs are not regular.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] On the other hand, the notion of electrical conductance that appears in electrical networks is unrelated to the conductance of a graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] The conductance was first defined by Mark Jerrum and Alistair Sinclair in 1988 to prove that the permanent of a matrix with entries from {0,1} has a polynomial-time approximation scheme.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] In the proof, Jerrum and Sinclair studied the Markov chain that switches between perfect and near-perfect matchings in bipartite graphs by adding or removing individual edges.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] They defined and used the conductance to prove that this Markov chain is rapidly mixing.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] This means that, after running the Markov chain for a polynomial number of steps, the resulting distribution is guaranteed to be close to the stationary distribution, which in this case is the uniform distribution on the set of all perfect and near-perfect matchings.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] This rapidly mixing Markov chain makes it possible in polynomial time to draw approximately uniform random samples from the set of all perfect matchings in the bipartite graph, which in turn gives rise to the polynomial-time approximation scheme for computing the permanent.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] For undirected d-regular graphs G without edge weights, the conductance $\varphi (G)$ is equal to the Cheeger constant $h(G)$ divided by d, that is, we have $\varphi (G)=h(G)/d$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] More generally, let G be a directed graph with n vertices, vertex set V , edge set E , and real weights $a_{ij}\geq 0$ on each edge $ij\in E$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Let $S\subseteq V$ be any vertex subset.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] If $\mathrm {vol} (S)$ equals 0 , then $a(S,{\bar {S}})$ also equals 0 and $\varphi (S)$ is defined as 1 .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] In practical applications, one often considers the conductance only over a cut.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] A common generalization of conductance is to handle the case of weights assigned to the edges: then the weights are added; if the weight is in the form of a resistance, then the reciprocal weights are added.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] The notion of conductance underpins the study of percolation in physics and other applied areas; thus, for example, the permeability of petroleum through porous rock can be modeled in terms of the conductance of a graph, with weights given by pore sizes.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Conductance also helps measure the quality of a Spectral clustering.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] The maximum among the conductance of clusters provides a bound which can be used, along with inter-cluster edge weight, to define a measure on the quality of clustering.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Intuitively, the conductance of a cluster (which can be seen as a set of vertices in a graph) should be low.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Apart from this, the conductance of the subgraph induced by a cluster (called "internal conductance") can be used as well.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] For an ergodic reversible Markov chain with an underlying graph *G*, the conductance is a way to measure how hard it is to leave a small set of nodes.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Formally, the conductance of a graph is defined as the minimum over all sets S of the capacity of S divided by the ergodic flow out of S .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Alistair Sinclair showed that conductance is closely tied to mixing time in ergodic reversible Markov chains.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] We can also view conductance in a more probabilistic way, as the probability of leaving a set of nodes given that we started in that set to begin with.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] where $\pi$ is the stationary distribution of the chain.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] In some literature, this quantity is also called the bottleneck ratio of *G*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/conductance-graph] Conductance is related to Markov chain mixing time in the reversible setting.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In the mathematical field of graph theory, the **Laplacian matrix**, also called the **graph Laplacian**, **admittance matrix**, **Kirchhoff matrix,** or **discrete Laplacian**, is a matrix representation of a graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Named after Pierre-Simon Laplace, the graph Laplacian matrix can be viewed as a matrix form of the negative discrete Laplace operator on a graph approximating the negative continuous Laplacian obtained by the finite difference method.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The Laplacian matrix relates to many functional graph properties.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Kirchhoff's theorem can be used to calculate the number of spanning trees for a given graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The sparsest cut of a graph can be approximated through the Fiedler vector — the eigenvector corresponding to the second smallest eigenvalue of the graph Laplacian — as established by Cheeger's inequality.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The spectral decomposition of the Laplacian matrix allows the construction of low-dimensional embeddings that appear in many machine learning applications and determines a spectral layout in graph drawing.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Graph-based signal processing is based on the graph Fourier transform that extends the traditional discrete Fourier transform by substituting the standard basis of complex sinusoids for eigenvectors of the Laplacian matrix of a graph corresponding to the signal.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The Laplacian matrix is the easiest to define for a simple graph but is more common in applications for an edge-weighted graph, i.e., with weights on its edges — the entries of the graph adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Spectral graph theory relates properties of a graph to a spectrum, i.e., eigenvalues and eigenvectors of matrices associated with the graph, such as its adjacency matrix or Laplacian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Imbalanced weights may undesirably affect the matrix spectrum, leading to the need of normalization — a column/row scaling of the matrix entries — resulting in normalized adjacency and Laplacian matrices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where *D* is the degree matrix, and *A* is the graph's adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Since ${\textstyle G}$ is a simple graph, ${\textstyle A}$ only contains 1s or 0s and its diagonal elements are all 0s.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Here is a simple example of a labelled, undirected graph and its Laplacian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] We observe for the undirected graph that both the adjacency matrix and the Laplacian matrix are symmetric and that the row- and column-sums of the Laplacian matrix are all zeros (which directly implies that the Laplacian matrix is singular).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In the directed graph, the adjacency matrix and Laplacian matrix are asymmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In its Laplacian matrix, column-sums or row-sums are zero, depending on whether the indegree or outdegree has been used.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where ${\textstyle B^{\textsf {T}}}$ is the matrix transpose of *B*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] An alternative product $B^{\textsf {T}}B$ defines the so-called ${\textstyle |e|\times |e|}$ *edge-based Laplacian,* as opposed to the original commonly used *vertex-based Laplacian* matrix *L*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The Laplacian matrix of a directed graph is by definition generally non-symmetric, while, e.g., traditional spectral clustering is primarily developed for undirected graphs with symmetric adjacency and Laplacian matrices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] A trivial approach to applying techniques requiring the symmetry is to turn the original directed graph into an undirected graph and build the Laplacian matrix for the latter.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] A vertex with a large degree, also called a *heavy node*, results in a large diagonal entry in the Laplacian matrix dominating the matrix properties.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Normalization is aimed to make the influence of such vertices more equal to that of other vertices, by dividing the entries of the Laplacian matrix by the vertex degrees.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] To avoid division by zero, isolated vertices with zero degrees are excluded from the process of the normalization.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where $D^{+}$ is the Moore–Penrose inverse of the degree matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The symmetrically normalized Laplacian matrix is symmetric if and only if the adjacency matrix is symmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where $D^{+}$ is the Moore–Penrose inverse.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The left or right normalized Laplacian matrix is symmetric if the adjacency matrix is symmetric and the graph is regular.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Otherwise, the left or right normalized Laplacian matrix is asymmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The example also demonstrates that if G has no isolated vertices, then $D^{+}A$ right stochastic and hence is the matrix of a random walk, so that the left normalized Laplacian $L^{\text{rw}}:=D^{+}L=I-D^{+}A$ has each row summing to zero.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Thus we sometimes alternatively call $L^{\text{rw}}$ the random-walk normalized Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In the less uncommonly used right normalized Laplacian $LD^{+}=I-AD^{+}$ each column sums to zero since $AD^{+}$ is left stochastic.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The left out-degree normalized Laplacian with row-sums all 0 relates to right stochastic $D_{\text{out}}^{+}A$ , while the right in-degree normalized Laplacian with column-sums all 0 contains left stochastic $AD_{\text{in}}^{+}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Common in applications graphs with weighted edges are conveniently defined by their adjacency matrices where values of the entries are numeric and no longer limited to zeros and ones.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Using correlation and anti-correlation between the data points naturally leads to both positive and negative weights.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Most definitions for simple graphs are trivially extended to the standard case of non-negative weights, while negative weights require more attention, especially in normalization.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where *D* is the degree matrix and *A* is the adjacency matrix of the graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Graph self-loops, manifesting themselves by non-zero entries on the main diagonal of the adjacency matrix, are allowed but do not affect the graph Laplacian values.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] For graphs with weighted edges one can define a weighted incidence matrix *B* and use it to construct the corresponding symmetric Laplacian as $L=BB^{\textsf {T}}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] An alternative cleaner approach, described here, is to separate the weights from the connectivity: continue using the incidence matrix as for regular graphs and introduce a matrix just holding the values of the weights.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] A spring system is an example of this model used in mechanics to describe a system of springs of given stiffnesses and unit length, where the values of the stiffnesses play the role of the weights of the graph edges.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] We now also define a diagonal ${\textstyle |e|\times |e|}$ matrix *W* containing the edge weights.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Just like for simple graphs, the Laplacian matrix of a directed weighted graph is by definition generally non-symmetric.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The symmetry can be enforced by turning the original directed graph into an undirected graph first before constructing the Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The sum of the out-degree Laplacian transposed and the in-degree Laplacian equals to the symmetric Laplacian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The goal of normalization is, like for simple graphs, to make the diagonal entries of the Laplacian matrix to be all unit, also scaling off-diagonal entries correspondingly.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In a weighted graph, a vertex may have a large degree because of a small number of connected edges but with large weights just as well as due to a large number of connected edges with unit weights.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Graph self-loops, i.e., non-zero entries on the main diagonal of the adjacency matrix, do not affect the graph Laplacian values, but may need to be counted for calculation of the normalization factors.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where *L* is the unnormalized Laplacian, *A* is the adjacency matrix, *D* is the degree matrix, and $D^{+}$ is the Moore–Penrose inverse.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Since the degree matrix *D* is diagonal, its reciprocal square root ${\textstyle (D^{+})^{1/2}}$ is just the diagonal matrix whose diagonal entries are the reciprocals of the square roots of the diagonal entries of *D*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] If all the edge weights are nonnegative then all the degree values are automatically also nonnegative and so every degree value has a unique positive square root.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The symmetrically normalized Laplacian is a symmetric matrix if and only if the adjacency matrix *A* is symmetric and the diagonal entries of *D* are nonnegative, in which case we can use the term the ***symmetric normalized Laplacian***.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Since the degree matrix *D* is diagonal, its inverse ${\textstyle D^{+}}$ is simply defined as a diagonal matrix, having diagonal entries which are the reciprocals of the corresponding diagonal entries of *D*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] For the isolated vertices (those with degree 0), a common choice is to set the corresponding element ${\textstyle L_{i,i}^{\text{rw}}}$ to 0.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The name of the random-walk normalized Laplacian comes from the fact that this matrix is ${\textstyle L^{\text{rw}}=I-P}$ , where ${\textstyle P=D^{+}A}$ is simply the transition matrix of a random walker on the graph, assuming non-negative weights.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] For example, let ${\textstyle e_{i}}$ denote the i-th standard basis vector.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Then ${\textstyle x=e_{i}P}$ is a probability vector representing the distribution of a random walker's locations after taking a single step from vertex ${\textstyle i}$ ; i.e., ${\textstyle x_{j}=\mathbb {P} \left(v_{i}\to v_{j}\right)}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] More generally, if the vector ${\textstyle x}$ is a probability distribution of the location of a random walker on the vertices of the graph, then ${\textstyle x'=xP^{t}}$ is the probability distribution of the walker after ${\textstyle t}$ steps.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The random walk normalized Laplacian can also be called the left normalized Laplacian $L^{\text{rw}}:=D^{+}L$ since the normalization is performed by multiplying the Laplacian by the normalization matrix $D^{+}$ on the left.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] It has each row summing to zero since $P=D^{+}A$ is right stochastic, assuming all the weights are non-negative.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Because ${\textstyle \lambda _{i}}$ can be written as the inner product of the vector ${\textstyle M\mathbf {v} _{i}}$ with itself, this shows that ${\textstyle \lambda _{i}\geq 0}$ and so the eigenvalues of ${\textstyle L}$ are all non-negative.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] i.e., ${\textstyle L^{\text{rw}}}$ is similar to the normalized Laplacian ${\textstyle L^{\text{sym}}}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] For this reason, even if ${\textstyle L^{\text{rw}}}$ is in general not symmetric, it has real eigenvalues — exactly the same as the eigenvalues of the normalized symmetric Laplacian ${\textstyle L^{\text{sym}}}$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The graph Laplacian matrix can be further viewed as a matrix form of the negative discrete Laplace operator on a graph approximating the negative continuous Laplacian operator obtained by the finite difference method.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Such an interpretation allows one, e.g., generalizing the Laplacian matrix to the case of graphs with an infinite number of vertices and edges, leading to a Laplacian matrix of an infinite size.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Notice the ordinary Laplacian is a generalized Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The Laplacian of a graph was first introduced to model electrical networks.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In an alternating current (AC) electrical network, real-valued resistances are replaced by complex-valued impedances.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The weight of edge (*i*, *j*) is, by convention, *minus* the reciprocal of the impedance directly between *i* and *j*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In models of such networks, the entries of the adjacency matrix are complex, but the Kirchhoff matrix remains symmetric, rather than being Hermitian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Such a matrix is usually called an "admittance matrix", denoted Y , rather than a "Laplacian".
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] This is one of the rare applications that give rise to complex symmetric matrices.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] There are other situations in which entries of the adjacency matrix are complex-valued, and the Laplacian does become a Hermitian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] which encode the edge direction into the phase in the complex plane.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] In the context of quantum physics, the magnetic Laplacian can be interpreted as the operator that describes the phenomenology of a free charged particle on a graph, which is subject to the action of a magnetic field and the parameter q is called electric charge.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where ${\textstyle I}$ is the identity matrix, ${\textstyle A}$ is the adjacency matrix, ${\textstyle D}$ is the degree matrix, and ${\textstyle s}$ is a (complex-valued) number.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] The standard Laplacian is just ${\textstyle \Delta (1)}$ and ${\textstyle \Delta (-1)=D+A}$ is the signless Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where D is the degree matrix, and A is the adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where ${\textstyle R}$ is the incidence matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] Q has a 0-eigenvector if and only if it has a bipartite connected component (isolated vertices being bipartite connected components).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] This has a solution where $\mathbf {x} \neq \mathbf {0}$ if and only if the graph has a bipartite connected component.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] An analogue of the Laplacian matrix can be defined for directed multigraphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/laplacian-matrix] where *D* is a diagonal matrix with *D**i*,*i* equal to the outdegree of vertex *i* and *A* is a matrix with *A**i*,*j* equal to the number of edges from *i* to *j* (including loops).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In multivariate statistics, **spectral clustering** techniques make use of the spectrum (eigenvalues) of the similarity matrix of the data to perform dimensionality reduction before clustering in fewer dimensions.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The similarity matrix is provided as an input and consists of a quantitative assessment of the relative similarity of each pair of points in the dataset.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In application to image segmentation, spectral clustering is known as segmentation-based object categorization.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Given an enumerated set of data points, the similarity matrix may be defined as a symmetric matrix A , where $A_{ij}\geq 0$ represents a measure of the similarity between data points with indices i and j .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The general approach to spectral clustering is to use a standard clustering method (there are many such methods, *k*-means is discussed below) on relevant eigenvectors of a Laplacian matrix of A .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] There are many different ways to define a Laplacian which have different mathematical interpretations, and so the clustering will also have different interpretations.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The eigenvectors that are relevant are the ones that correspond to several smallest eigenvalues of the Laplacian except for the smallest eigenvalue which will have a value of 0.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] For computational efficiency, these eigenvectors are often computed as the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest several eigenvalues of a function of the Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is well known to relate to partitioning of a mass-spring system, where each mass is associated with a data point and each spring stiffness corresponds to a weight of an edge describing a similarity of the two related data points, as in the spring system.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The goal of normalization is making the diagonal entries of the Laplacian matrix to be all unit, also scaling off-diagonal entries correspondingly.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] A popular normalized spectral clustering technique is the **normalized cuts algorithm** or *Shi–Malik algorithm* introduced by Jianbo Shi and Jitendra Malik, commonly used for image segmentation.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] and can also be used for spectral clustering.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] A mathematically equivalent algorithm takes the eigenvector u corresponding to the largest eigenvalue of the random walk normalized adjacency matrix $P=D^{-1}A$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Knowing the n -by- k matrix V of selected eigenvectors, mapping — called spectral embedding — of the original n data points is performed to a k -dimensional vector space using the rows of V .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Now the analysis is reduced to clustering vectors with k components, which may be done in various ways.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In the simplest case $k=1$ , the selected single eigenvector v , called the Fiedler vector, corresponds to the second smallest eigenvalue.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Using the components of $v,$ one can place all points whose component in v is positive in the set $B_{+}$ and the rest in $B_{-}$ , thus bi-partitioning the graph and labeling the data points with two labels.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The algorithm can be used for hierarchical clustering by repeatedly partitioning the subsets in the same fashion.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In the general case $k>1$ , any vector clustering technique can be used, e.g., DBSCAN.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] For large-sized graphs, the second eigenvalue of the (normalized) graph Laplacian matrix is often ill-conditioned, leading to slow convergence of iterative eigenvalue solvers.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Preconditioning is a key technology accelerating the convergence, e.g., in the matrix-free LOBPCG method.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering has been successfully applied on large graphs by first identifying their community structure, and then clustering communities.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is closely related to nonlinear dimensionality reduction, and dimension reduction techniques such as locally-linear embedding can be used to reduce errors from noise or outliers.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Denoting the number of the data points by n , it is important to estimate the memory footprint and compute time, or number of arithmetic operations (AO) performed, as a function of n .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] No matter the algorithm of the spectral clustering, the two main costly items are the construction of the graph Laplacian and determining its k eigenvectors for the spectral embedding.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The last step — determining the labels from the n -by- k matrix of eigenvectors — is typically the least expensive requiring only $kn$ AO and creating just a n -by- 1 vector of the labels in memory.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The need to construct the graph Laplacian is common for all distance- or correlation-based clustering methods.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Computing the eigenvectors is specific to spectral clustering only.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The graph Laplacian can be and commonly is constructed from the adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The construction can be performed matrix-free, i.e., without explicitly forming the matrix of the graph Laplacian and no AO.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] It can also be performed in-place of the adjacency matrix without increasing the memory footprint.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Either way, the costs of constructing the graph Laplacian is essentially determined by the costs of constructing the n -by- n graph adjacency matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Moreover, a normalized Laplacian has exactly the same eigenvectors as the normalized adjacency matrix, but with the order of the eigenvalues reversed.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Thus, instead of computing the eigenvectors corresponding to the smallest eigenvalues of the normalized Laplacian, one can equivalently compute the eigenvectors corresponding to the largest eigenvalues of the normalized adjacency matrix, without even talking about the Laplacian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Naive constructions of the graph adjacency matrix, e.g., using the RBF kernel, make it dense, thus requiring $n^{2}$ memory and $n^{2}$ AO to determine each of the $n^{2}$ entries of the matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Nystrom method can be used to approximate the similarity matrix, but the approximate matrix is not elementwise positive, i.e. cannot be interpreted as a distance-based similarity.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Algorithms to construct the graph adjacency matrix as a sparse matrix are typically based on a nearest neighbor search, which estimate or sample a neighborhood of a given data point for nearest neighbors, and compute non-zero entries of the adjacency matrix by comparing only pairs of the neighbors.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The cost of computing the n -by- k (with $k\ll n$ ) matrix of selected eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian is normally proportional to the cost of multiplication of the n -by- n graph Laplacian matrix by a vector, which varies greatly whether the graph Laplacian matrix is dense or sparse.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] For the dense case the cost thus is $O(n^{2})$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The very commonly cited in the literature cost $O(n^{3})$ comes from choosing $k=n$ and is clearly misleading, since, e.g., in a hierarchical spectral clustering $k=1$ as determined by the Fiedler vector.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Moreover, matrix-free eigenvalue solvers such as LOBPCG can efficiently run in parallel, e.g., on multiple GPUs with distributed memory, resulting not only in high quality clusters, which spectral clustering is famous for, but also top performance.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Free software implementing spectral clustering is available in large open source projects like scikit-learn using LOBPCG with multigrid preconditioning or ARPACK, MLlib for pseudo-eigenvector clustering using the power iteration method, and R.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The ideas behind spectral clustering may not be immediately obvious.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] It may be useful to highlight relationships with other methods.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In particular, it can be described in the context of kernel clustering methods, which reveals several similarities with other approaches.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is closely related to the **k-means** algorithm, especially in how cluster assignments are ultimately made.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Although the two methods differ fundamentally in their initial formulations—spectral clustering being graph-based and k-means being centroid-based—the connection becomes clear when spectral clustering is viewed through the lens of **kernel methods**.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In particular, **weighted kernel k-means** provides a key theoretical bridge between the two.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Kernel k-means is a generalization of the standard k-means algorithm, where data is implicitly mapped into a high-dimensional feature space through a kernel function, and clustering is performed in that space.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering, especially the normalized versions, performs a similar operation by mapping the input data (or graph nodes) to a lower-dimensional space defined by the **eigenvectors of the graph Laplacian**.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] These eigenvectors correspond to the solution of a **relaxation** of the **normalized cut** or other graph partitioning objectives.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Mathematically, the objective function minimized by spectral clustering can be shown to be equivalent to the objective function of weighted kernel k-means in this transformed space.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] This was formally established in works such as where they demonstrated that normalized cuts are equivalent to a weighted version of kernel k-means applied to the rows of the normalized Laplacian’s eigenvector matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Because of this equivalence, **spectral clustering can be viewed as performing kernel k-means in the eigenspace defined by the graph Laplacian**.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] This theoretical insight has practical implications: the final clustering step in spectral clustering typically involves running the **standard k-means algorithm** on the rows of the matrix formed by the first k eigenvectors of the Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] These rows can be thought of as embedding each data point or node in a low-dimensional space where the clusters are more well-separated and hence, easier for k-means to detect.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Additionally, **multi-level methods** have been developed to directly optimize this shared objective function.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] These methods work by iteratively **coarsening** the graph to reduce problem size, solving the problem on a coarse graph, and then **refining** the solution on successively finer graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] This leads to more efficient optimization for large-scale problems, while still capturing the global structure preserved by the spectral embedding.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering is also conceptually related to **DBSCAN** (Density-Based Spatial Clustering of Applications with Noise), particularly in the special case where the spectral method is used to identify **connected graph components** of a graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] In this trivial case—where the goal is to identify subsets of nodes with **no interconnecting edges** between them—the spectral method effectively reduces to a connectivity-based clustering approach, much like DBSCAN.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] DBSCAN operates by identifying **density-connected regions** in the input space: points that are reachable from one another via a sequence of neighboring points within a specified radius (ε), and containing a minimum number of points (minPts).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The algorithm excels at discovering clusters of arbitrary shape and separating out noise without needing to specify the number of clusters in advance.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] This mirrors DBSCAN's ability to isolate **density-connected components**.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] The zeroth eigenvectors of the unnormalized Laplacian correspond to these components, with one eigenvector per connected region.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Therefore, spectral clustering in this regime behaves like a **spectral version of DBSCAN**, especially in sparse graphs or when constructing ε-neighborhood graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] While DBSCAN operates directly in the data space using density estimates, spectral clustering transforms the data into an eigenspace where **global structure and connectivity** are emphasized.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Both methods are non-parametric in spirit, and neither assumes convex cluster shapes, which further supports their conceptual alignment.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Ravi Kannan, Santosh Vempala and Adrian Vetta proposed a bicriteria measure to define the quality of a given clustering.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] They said that a clustering was an (α, ε)-clustering if the conductance of each cluster (in the clustering) was at least α and the weight of the inter-cluster edges was at most ε fraction of the total weight of all the edges in the graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] They also look at two approximation algorithms in the same paper.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Spectral clustering as a machine learning method was popularized by Shi & Malik and Ng, Jordan, & Weiss.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] Ideas and network measures related to spectral clustering also play an important role in a number of applications apparently different from clustering problems.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-clustering] For instance, networks with stronger spectral partitions take longer to converge in opinion-updating models used in sociology and economics.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] In mathematics, **spectral graph theory** is the study of the properties of a graph in relationship to the characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, and eigenvectors of matrices associated with the graph, such as its adjacency matrix or Laplacian matrix.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The adjacency matrix of a simple undirected graph is a real symmetric matrix and is therefore orthogonally diagonalizable; its eigenvalues are real algebraic integers.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] While the adjacency matrix depends on the vertex labeling, its spectrum is a graph invariant, although not a complete one.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Spectral graph theory is also concerned with graph parameters that are defined via multiplicities of eigenvalues of matrices associated to the graph, such as the Colin de Verdière number.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Two graphs are called **cospectral** or **isospectral** if the adjacency matrices of the graphs are isospectral, that is, if the adjacency matrices have the same eigenvalues with multiplicity.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Cospectral graphs need not be isomorphic, but isomorphic graphs are always cospectral.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] A graph G is said to be determined by its spectrum if any other graph with the same spectrum as G is isomorphic to G .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Two graphs are said to be cospectral mates if they are cospectral but are non-isomorphic.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The smallest pair of cospectral mates is {*K*1,4, *C*4 ∪ *K*1}, comprising the 5-vertex star and the graph union of the 4-vertex cycle and the single-vertex graph.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The first example of cospectral graphs was reported by Collatz and Sinogowitz in 1957.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The smallest pair of polyhedral cospectral mates are enneahedra with eight vertices each.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Almost all trees are cospectral, i.e., as the number of vertices grows, the fraction of trees for which there exists a cospectral tree goes to 1.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] A pair of regular graphs are cospectral if and only if their complements are cospectral.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] A pair of distance-regular graphs are cospectral if and only if they have the same intersection array.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Cospectral graphs can also be constructed by means of the Sunada method.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Another important source of cospectral graphs are the point-collinearity graphs and the line-intersection graphs of point-line geometries.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] These graphs are always cospectral but are often non-isomorphic.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The famous Cheeger's inequality from Riemannian geometry has a discrete analogue involving the Laplacian matrix; this is perhaps the most important theorem in spectral graph theory and one of the most useful facts in algorithmic applications.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] It approximates the sparsest cut of a graph through the second eigenvalue of its Laplacian.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The **Cheeger constant** (also **Cheeger number** or **isoperimetric number**) of a graph is a numerical measure of whether or not a graph has a "bottleneck".
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The Cheeger constant as a measure of "bottleneckedness" is of great interest in many areas: for example, constructing well-connected networks of computers, card shuffling, and low-dimensional topology (in particular, the study of hyperbolic 3-manifolds).
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] where the minimum is over all nonempty sets *S* of at most *n*/2 vertices and ∂(*S*) is the *edge boundary* of *S*, i.e., the set of edges with exactly one endpoint in *S*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] When the graph *G* is *d*-regular, there is a relationship between *h*(*G*) and the spectral gap *d* − λ2 of *G*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] This inequality is closely related to the Cheeger bound for Markov chains and can be seen as a discrete version of Cheeger's inequality in Riemannian geometry.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] where ${\mathrm {vol} }(Y)$ is the sum of degrees of vertices in Y .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] There is an eigenvalue bound for independent sets in regular graphs, originally due to Alan J.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Suppose that G is a k -regular graph on n vertices with least eigenvalue $\lambda _{\mathrm {min} }$ .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] This bound has been applied to establish e.g. algebraic proofs of the Erdős–Ko–Rado theorem and its analogue for intersecting families of subspaces over finite fields.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] This a consequence of a more general inequality (pp.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] 109 in ): ${\mathrm {vol} }(X)\leq (1-{\frac {1}{\lambda '_{\mathrm {max} }}}){\mathrm {vol} }(V(G))$ where X is an independent set of vertices and ${\mathrm {vol} }(Y)$ denotes the sum of degrees of vertices in Y .
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Spectral graph theory emerged in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] Besides graph theoretic research on the relationship between structural and spectral properties of graphs, another major source was research in quantum chemistry, but the connections between these two lines of work were not discovered until much later.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The 1980 monograph *Spectra of Graphs* by Cvetković, Doob, and Sachs summarised nearly all research to date in the area.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] In 1988 it was updated by the survey *Recent Results in the Theory of Graph Spectra*.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The 3rd edition of *Spectra of Graphs* (1995) contains a summary of the further recent contributions to the subject.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] The field of discrete geometric analysis, created and developed by Toshikazu Sunada in the 2000s, deals with spectral graph theory in terms of discrete Laplacians associated with weighted graphs.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] It finds application in various other fields, including shape analysis.
[src:spectral-graph-theory/spectral-graph-theory] A more recent development in spectral graph theory is vertex-frequency analysis, a set of techniques for solving problems in many real-life applications such as signal processing.
